
1. Phishing
Definition
Phishing is a cyberattack in which attackers trick people into revealing sensitive information such as passwords, banking details, or personal data by pretending to be a trusted organization.
Real-World Example
A user receives an email claiming to be from a bank asking them to click a link and verify their account details. The link leads to a fake website designed to steal login credentials.
Prevention Methods
•	Do not click suspicious links.
•	Verify the sender before responding to emails.
•	Enable Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA).
•	Check website URLs carefully.

2. Malware
Definition
Malware is malicious software designed to damage, disrupt, or gain unauthorized access to a computer system.
Real-World Example
A user downloads a free software program from an untrusted website, which secretly installs malware on the computer.
Prevention Methods
•	Install and update antivirus software.
•	Download software only from trusted sources.
•	Keep the operating system updated.
•	Avoid opening suspicious attachments.

3. Ransomware
Definition
Ransomware is a type of malware that encrypts files and demands payment from the victim to restore access.
Real-World Example
The WannaCry ransomware attack infected thousands of computers worldwide and locked users out of their files until a ransom was paid.
Prevention Methods
•	Maintain regular backups of important data.
•	Keep software and systems updated.
•	Avoid clicking unknown links or attachments.
•	Use security software and firewalls.

4. Social Engineering
Definition
Social engineering is a technique used by attackers to manipulate people into revealing confidential information or performing actions that compromise security.
Real-World Example
An attacker pretends to be an IT support employee and asks an employee for their login credentials.
Prevention Methods
•	Verify the identity of anyone requesting sensitive information.
•	Never share passwords.
•	Provide cybersecurity awareness training.
•	Be cautious of unexpected requests.

5. Data Breach
Definition
A data breach occurs when sensitive or confidential information is accessed, stolen, or exposed without authorization.
Real-World Example
A company database containing customer names, email addresses, and passwords is accessed by hackers and leaked online.
Prevention Methods
•	Use strong and unique passwords.
•	Enable Multi-Factor Authentication.
•	Encrypt sensitive data.
•	Regularly update and patch systems.
•	Limit access to sensitive information.
